    type='think',
    think='The app is STILL on the login page after the flow completes! The logi
n button was tapped but the app didn\'t navigate away. This is very strange.\n\n
Let me think about what could cause this:\n1. The `onPressed` callback is not be
ing triggered by Maestro\'s `tapOn`\n2. The login API is failing silently\n3. Th
e app has some issue with navigation\n\nWait, I just realized something importan
t. Looking at the login_page.dart:\n```dart\nBlocBuilder<AuthBloc, AuthState>(\n
 builder: (context, state) {\n    final isLoading = state is AuthAuthenticating;
\n    return SwButton(\n      text: \'登录\',\n      variant: SwButtonVariant.fi
lled,\n      isLoading: isLoading,\n      onPressed: isLoading ? null : _onLogin
,\n    );\n  },\n),\n```\n\nAnd looking at the screenshot - the button does NOT 
show a loading indicator. If `_onLogin` was called, it would emit `AuthAuthentic
ating` and the button would show loading. Since there\'s no loading indicator, `
_onLogin` was NOT called.\n\nWhy would `tapOn: "登录"` not trigger `_onLogin`?\n
\nLooking at the `SwButton` implementation, it uses `ElevatedButton`. Maestro\'s
`tapOn` for text should tap the button. But wait - in the `login-as-test-user.ya
ml`, before `tapOn: "登录"`, there\'s `hideKeyboard`. \n\nCould `hideKeyboard` b
e causing the button to not receive the tap? Or could there be some overlay?\n\n
Actually, looking at the screenshot, there\'s the dev tools toggle button in the
bottom right corner. But that shouldn\'t interfere with the login button.\n\nWai
t! I see it now. Looking at `login-as-test-user.yaml`:\n```yaml\n- tapOn: "手机
号"\n- inputText: "13800138000"\n```\n\nWhen Maestro does `inputText`, it might 
be appending to the existing text in the field. But the field was empty, so it s
hould be fine. However, `inputText` in Maestro works by sending key events. For 
Flutter, this should work.\n\nBut here\'s a crucial observation: the `tapOn: "登
录"` might not be working because Maestro is tapping on the text "登录" which is
inside the button, but the `ElevatedButton` might not be receiving the tap corre
ctly for some reason.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be simpler. Let me ch
eck if `tapOn: "登录"` is finding the right element. Looking at the Maestro logs
, it does find the element with `accessibilityText: 登录`. The tap coordinates a
re `(540, 1145)` which is in the center of the button bounds `[42,1082][1038,120
8]`.\n\nBut wait - in Flutter, `ElevatedButton` uses `onPressed`. Maestro\'s tap
should trigger it. Let me check if there\'s any known issue with Maestro and Flu
tter `ElevatedButton`.\n\nActually, I just had another idea. Could the issue be 
that `hideKeyboard` causes the layout to shift, and the button tap happens befor
e the layout settles? Or maybe `hideKeyboard` in Maestro doesn\'t work well with
Flutter and causes focus issues?\n\nLet me test by removing `hideKeyboard` from 
